	<h1>
The Business of Play
</h1>
	<div class="page-title-hline">&nbsp;</div>
	










<!-- MAIN CONTENT AREA - START -->



		<div class="floatright">
			<br class="hide" />
<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="sidebar" --><!-- FCKEDITOR_sidebar --><!-- /FCKEDITOR_sidebar --> <!-- InstanceEndEditable -->

<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="Sidebar" --><!-- InstanceEndEditable --><br class="hide" />
			</div>


			<div class="contentcolumn">
				<br class="hide" />
<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="maincontent" --><!-- FCKEDITOR_maincontent --><!-- /FCKEDITOR_maincontent -->

	<div id="entry-374">
		<div class="entry-content">
			<div class="entry-body">
				
<img alt="DSC_4658.jpg" src="http://newsfeed.encs.concordia.ca/encs_test/DSC_4658.jpg" class="mt-image-right" style="float: right; margin: 0pt 0pt 20px 20px;" width="220" height="331" />How many people can say that the games they played as a child directly influenced their career path as an adult? The educational toys that littered Martin Ouellet's bedroom floor as a kid may not have predicted that he would one day found the world the leading provider of on-demand talent management solutions -- but they certainly helped point him in that direction.<br /><br />Growing up a bright, young boy in Sainte-Foy, Ouellet explored his technical aptitude through an Electronics 2000 toy set. It gave him hands-on experience in the domain of electrical engineering, allowing him the freedom to build his own capacitors and metres. "All the little guys had one: it really marked me," Ouellet recalls with a smile.Those early days of educational playing led to a love of math, physics and chemistry. "I had a natural inclination towards ngineering," he explains. The fact that his father was an elevator technician also helped inspire the young Ouellet to pursue a technical program at CEGEP.<br /><br />As a fresh college graduate with a technical background, Ouellet decided to pursue computer engineering. It was the mid-1980s and computers were exploding in popularity. At the time, only two programs in computer engineering were offered in Canada: one at Waterloo, the other at Concordia. Weighing his options, Ouellet opted for the more affordable and accessible option -- and never looked back! After learning the ropes and getting a strong grasp of the fundamentals during his first two years at Concordia, Ouellet really found his rhythm when classes became more targeted. "Suddenly we were studying algorithms, computer<br />databases, architecture, networking... It was at that point that I really felt like we were on the cutting edge. We were doing something that was really new,<br />something that was going to be required by industry."<br /><br />20 years after graduating with a BEng in Computer Engineering, Ouellet's personal evolution has been marked by ongoing accomplishment. Recruited right out of school by Bell Canada, he spent two years working for the telecommunications giant before moving to Quebec as product manager and chief of the development&nbsp; department for a company called Exfo. But it wasn't long before Ouellet, with his talent for technology and management capabilities, decided to found his<br />own company.<br /><br />In 1996, Ouellet established Viasite. Although the first years were a struggle, the company would become Canada's most successful job board. As he watched business grow, Ouellet realized employers needed customizable software to streamline their recruitment efforts and so changed the business plan and raised tens of millions of dollars in venture capital money to launch a new set of products, resulting in increased expansion for Ouellet's company, which went public in 2005 on the NASDAQ under the name "Taleo" (a neologism coined by Ouellet, which combines "talent," plus the Greek word "eo," which translates as "moving forward").<br /><br />Today, Taleo has more than 1,200 employees and boasts some impressive numbers: yearly revenue of nearly $250 million; more than 5,000 clients in 187&nbsp; ountries; over nine million successful hires are processed through their systems; and a market cap of $1.5 billion. Ouellet is delighted with the company's astounding progress, especially given its humble beginnings. "I met with success because I surrounded myself with extremely competent people. I associated with people who had expertise and money and I went to find other investments. C'est vraiment trippant!" he laughs.<br /><br />In 2006, with business booming and Taleo's headquarters relocated to San Francisco, Ouellet decided that it was time to move onto new challenges. That's when he founded a new company named Genia. The small company has spent the last few years in development and is now poised to launch itself head first into the exciting new domain of knowledge-powered online games. Although the details of the project remain confidential, a sneak peek can be found at www.genia.com.<br /><br />Ouellet is certain that it will revolutionize online gaming. "We feel like we're really ahead of the pack with this product, starting something new with this game, using your knowledge. We want to build the best, most innovative product in the world -- and have fun doing it!"<br />

			</div>
